              },
              {
                "heading": "2. Negative Feedback Loops",
                "content": "**How homeostasis works:** Negative Feedback Loops\n\nThink of the thermostat from Stage 1:\n1. **Sensor** detects the current condition (thermometer reads room temp)\n2. **Control center** compares it to the set point (22¬∞C target)\n3. **If too low:** Effector activates (heater turns ON)\n4. **If too high:** Effector activates (heater turns OFF)\n5. **Return to set point:** Effector stops, system goes quiet\n\n**The 'Negative' Part:**\nThe response OPPOSES the change:\n- Too cold? ‚Üí Generate heat\n- Too hot? ‚Üí Release heat\n- Too high blood sugar? ‚Üí Lower it\n- Too low blood sugar? ‚Üí Raise it\n\n**Critical Point:** Negative feedback prevents constant oscillation. The system only acts when there's a problem, then STOPS when fixed.",
                "diagram": {
                  "type": "flowchart",
                  "description": "Negative Feedback Loop: Change detected ‚Üí Receptors sense change ‚Üí Control center processes ‚Üí Effectors respond ‚Üí Condition returns to normal ‚Üí System stops responding"
                }
              },
              {
                "heading": "3. Components of a Feedback Loop",
                "content": "Every homeostatic system has three parts:\n\n**‚ë† RECEPTORS (Sensors)**\n- Detect changes in the environment (internal or external)\n- Examples: Temperature receptors in skin, glucose sensors in pancreas\n\n**‚ë° CONTROL CENTER (Brain/Coordination)**\n- Receives information from receptors\n- Compares current state to set point\n- Sends instructions to effectors\n- Examples: Hypothalamus (temperature control), Pancreas (blood sugar)\n\n**‚ë¢ EFFECTORS (Response System)**\n- Carry out the response to correct the change\n- Examples: Muscles (shivering), Sweat glands (cooling), Blood vessels (widen/narrow)",
                "table": {
                  "headers": ["Component", "Role", "Example (Temperature Control)"],
                  "rows": [
                    ["Receptors", "Detect change", "Thermoreceptors in skin sense cold air"],
                    ["Control Center", "Process & decide", "Hypothalamus compares to 37¬∞C set point"],
                    ["Effectors", "Execute response", "Muscles shiver to generate heat"]
                  ]
                }
              },
              {
                "heading": "4. Examples of Homeostasis",
                "content": "**A. Temperature Regulation (Thermoregulation)**\n- Set point: 37¬∞C\n- Too hot? ‚Üí Sweat, blood vessels widen (vasodilation)\n- Too cold? ‚Üí Shiver, blood vessels narrow (vasoconstriction)\n\n**B. Blood Glucose Regulation**\n- Set point: 4-6 mmol/L\n- Too high? ‚Üí Pancreas releases insulin ‚Üí Cells absorb glucose\n- Too low? ‚Üí Pancreas releases glucagon ‚Üí Liver releases stored glucose\n\n**C. Water Balance (Osmoregulation)**\n- Set point: Balanced water and salt levels\n- Too much water? ‚Üí Kidneys produce more urine (dilute)\n- Too little water? ‚Üí Kidneys conserve water, urine becomes concentrated\n\n**D. pH Balance**\n- Set point: Blood pH 7.35-7.45\n- Too acidic? ‚Üí Lungs breathe faster (remove CO‚ÇÇ), kidneys excrete H‚Å∫ ions\n- Too alkaline? ‚Üí Lungs breathe slower, kidneys retain H‚Å∫ ions",
                "realWorld": "Elite athletes train their bodies to maintain homeostasis under extreme stress. A marathon runner's body must manage heat, water loss, glucose depletion, and lactic acid buildup simultaneously ‚Äî all while keeping vital organs functioning!"
              },
